                            <container4
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title_copy_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T17:00:58.796-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-04-22T13:45:51.246-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Building new possibilities in cancer research"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-08-29T12:05:28.679-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>&lt;span>Just a decade or two ago, a person diagnosed with blood cancer faced a narrow path forward: chemotherapy, radiation, perhaps a bone marrow transplant. Treatment was delivered in a hospital setting, with a 5-year survival rate in the teens.&lt;/span>&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>&lt;span>Flash forward to today. Scientific innovation has greatly changed the treatment landscape for blood cancer, driven primarily by targeted therapies that disrupt cancer cell growth and survival.&lt;/span>&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Five-year survival rates for leukemia alone have nearly doubled from 34 percent in the mid-1970s to 66 percent in the early-mid 2000s, according to the&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.lls.org/facts-and-statistics/facts-and-statistics-overview&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; style=&quot;background-color: rgb(255,255,255);&quot;>Leukemia &amp;amp; Lymphoma Society.&lt;/a>&lt;br>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Treatment advancements in the past 10 years have proven life-changing for people with chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL), particularly for Ben Greenlee. At his time of diagnosis over a decade ago, his doctor did something that may seem counterintuitive: he told Ben not to treat his blood cancer.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“He said, ‘Well, we don’t really have options now, but by the time you need it, there’ll be better options out there,’” Greenlee says. “Which didn’t sound as hopeful as he meant it. It felt like a death sentence.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>As it turns out, Greenlee’s doctor was indeed correct and now he has the right treatment plan.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>While great strides have occurred, cancer researchers are motivated to continue advancing science for those with more aggressive and difficult-to-treat diseases, according to Andy Souers, Ph.D., distinguished research fellow, AbbVie.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“The field of oncology is really in a renaissance time right now,” he says. “While there has been progress over the last decade, there is still a ton of unmet need and work ahead of us. At AbbVie, we won't settle for incremental progress. We will continue to transform standards of care for every single patient.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <quote jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"/>
                            </container4>
